Nicholas. Thanks everyone for your help. . Thanks for the comment. I definitely see the reason behind your suggestion. We can avoid early exiting this method by being a bit cleverer. :) 
With the snippet above, there's a possible situation that targetURL is initialized with an nil. 
You can write [NSURL URLWithString: nil]; and it compiles, but Xcode will give you this warning Null passed to a callee that requires a non-null argument. Xcode is telling us we should not pass an nil value into that method and I do like to keep the warnings in a codebase as few as possible and to call methods properly.
I think I might have an solution to avoid that situation (initializing NSURL with nil).
What do you think of the following?
```objective-c
  NSURL *targetURL;
  NSString * targetURLString = applinkData[@"target_url"];
if (targetURLString == nil || ![targetURLString isKindOfClass: [NSString class]]) {
     targetURL = nil;
  } else {
    targetURL = [NSURL URLWithString:applinkData[@"target_url"]];
  }
```
This way, we do not early exit this method even when targetURLString is nil or is not of type NSString and we do not crash the SDK plus the apps.. @mangofever I have updated the code to include the change proposed above. Please review again. Thanks..

